     * [file://localhost/Users/admin/Pros/sh/awesome/awe_raw/progressive-e
       nhancement-resources#related-articles]Related Articles

The Concept

   [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progressive_enhancement]Progressive
   Enhancement means gradually improving the user experience after
   verifying the target environment (e.g. browser) is capable of it. Start
   with content and ensure you maintain functionality & accessibility.
     * [http://cognition.happycog.com/article/progressive-enhancement-its-
       about-the-content]Progressive Enhancement: It's about the content -
       Sharing content is the core of the web. Progressive Enhancement
       ensures access to content.
     * [https://www.nngroup.com/articles/enhancement/]The Role of
       Enhancement in Web Design - From the concept of enhancement to the
       criteria and rules for enriching the user interface.
     * [http://alistapart.com/article/understandingprogressiveenhancement]
       Understanding Progressive Enhancement - Apply technologies in an
       intelligent way, layer-upon-layer, to craft an amazing experience.
     * [https://www.filamentgroup.com/dwpe/]Designing with Progressive
       Enhancement - The book (400+ pages) on Progressive Enhancement.
     * [http://adaptivewebdesign.info/2nd-edition/]Adaptive Web Design -
       Book on Progressive Enhancement from content to design and
       interaction.
     * [http://diveinto.html5doctor.com/detect.html]Detecting (HTML5)
       features - Intro to different feature detection techniques with
       examples and demos.
     * [https://infrequently.org/2015/06/progressive-apps-escaping-tabs-wi
       thout-losing-our-soul/]Progressive Web Apps - Enhancing web sites
       into native-like apps (progressive, not hybrid).

Strategies

   You can apply Progressive Enhancement in different ways:
     * [https://articles.uie.com/progressive_enhancement/]The Content-out
       Approach - Provide wide access to content without technological
       restrictions.
     * [https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/technology/using-progressive-enh
       ancement#make-the-page-usable-with-only-html]Make the page usable
       with only HTML - This sets the baseline for every device and
       browser.
     * [http://alistapart.com/article/testdriven]Test Driven Progressive
       Enhancement - Core functional experience enhanced after testing
       capabilities.
     * [http://responsivenews.co.uk/post/18948466399/cutting-the-mustard]C
       ut the mustard - Set a threshold for collection of enhancements.
     * [https://www.filamentgroup.com/lab/grade-the-components.html]Grade
       components, not browsers - Component level feature tests and
       enhancements.
     * [http://www.html5rocks.com/en/tutorials/detection/]Feature vs
       Browser vs Form factor detection - As different strategies to tune
       your app to its environment.
     * [https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2014/07/server-side-device-detect
       ion-with-javascript/]Server-side device detection - Use user-agent
       and other HTTP header info combined with a device database to
       conditionally serve files.
     * [https://addyosmani.com/blog/writing-polyfills/]Writing polyfills -
       If your baseline is still too high for some browsers, consider
       [https://remysharp.com/2010/10/08/what-is-a-polyfill]polyfills (aka
       [https://twitter.com/SlexAxton/status/25600963629]Regressive
       Enhancement).
     * [https://medium.com/google-developers/instant-loading-web-apps-with
       -an-application-shell-architecture-7c0c2f10c73]Application Shell
       Architecture - Setup for instant loading web apps.

Feature Detection

   Before you try to enhance the experience, you need to ensure the
   environment is capable of the enhancement. You test this by performing
   feature detections:
     * [https://www.sitepoint.com/an-introduction-to-css-supports-rule-fea
       ture-queries/]CSS feature queries
       ([https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/API/CSS/supports]CSS.su
       pports() &
       [https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/@supports]@suppor
       ts()) - Natively test if specific CSS feature is supported using JS
       method or CSS declaration.
     * [https://www.npmjs.com/package/feature-detect-es6]Feature Detect
       ES6 - Detect which ES2015 features are available.
     * [https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/SVG/Attribute/require
       dFeatures]SVG requiredFeatures - Render SVG elements only if their
       [requiredFeatures] evaluate to true.
     * [https://modernizr.com/]Modernizr - Extensive feature detection
       suite (supports custom builds).
     * [http://featurejs.com/]Feature.js - Lightweight feature detection
       suite.
     * [http://conditionerjs.com/]Conditioner.js - Conditionally load JS
       modules based on directives in HTML attributes.
     * [https://www.filamentgroup.com/lab/introducing-enhancejs-smarter-sa
       fer-apply-progressive-enhancement.html]EnhanceJS - Lets you
       asynchronously load CSS & JS after a set pre-defined feature tests.

Support Tables

   Different environments (platforms, browsers, versions) have different
   capabilities. Support tables tell you what capabilities each
   environment has. Knowing the level of support can help you weigh an
   enhancement against the effort and impact of its implementation.
     * [https://platform.html5.org/]The Web Platform - Overview of browser
       technologies with links to docs and test suites.
     * [http://caniuse.com/]Can I use ...? - Compare feature
       implementations and limitations across desktop & mobile browsers.
     * [http://www.iwanttouse.com/]I want to use ... - Figure out the
       browser support of combinations of features.
     * [http://html5test.com/]HTML5 Test - Test and compare HTML5 feature
       support across browsers.
     * [http://css3test.com/]CSS3 Test - Fine-grained tests for CSS3
       feature support of your current browser.
     * [http://stateofwebtype.com/]State of Web Type - Support tables for
       type and typographic features on the web.
     * [http://fontfamily.io/]Font Family Reunion - Compatibility tables
       for default local (system) fonts.
     * [http://html5accessibility.com/]HTML5 Accessibility - Compare
       feature support of HTML5 tags, input types and properties across
       major browsers.
     * [https://www.powermapper.com/tests/screen-readers/aria/]WAI-ARIA
       Screen reader compatibility - ARIA roles and attributes support for
       different screen reader and browser combinations.
     * [https://whatwebcando.today/]What web can do today - Lists and
       checks modern web APIs like access to device system, sensors and
       actuators.
     * [https://nolanlawson.github.io/html5workertest/]HTML5 Worker test -
       Compare which APIs are supported in Web Workers and Service Workers
       across browsers.
     * [http://html5please.com/]HTML5 Please - Explore features with
       recommendations and links to polyfills.
     * [https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/platform/cata
       log/]API Catalog - Lets you compare implementation of API
       specifications in major desktop browsers.
     * [http://kangax.github.io/compat-table/]Kangax's ECMAScript
       compatibility table - Overview of JavaScript feature support across
       browsers and other runtimes.
     * [http://node.green/]Node compatibility table - Overview of
       JavaScript feature support across NodeJS versions.
     * [https://jakearchibald.github.io/isserviceworkerready/]Is service
       worker ready? - Overview of support for all features involved in
       the core technology behind Progressive Web Apps.
     * [https://ispwaready.toxicjohann.com/]Is PWA ready? - Overview of
       support for the core and related technologies behind Progressive
       Web Apps for both popular global and many Chinese browsers.
     * [http://iswebrtcreadyyet.com/]Is WebRTC ready yet? - Overview of
       support for the different browser features behind real time
       communication.
     * [https://iswebvrready.org/]Is WebVR ready? - Overview of support of
       different browser features behind WebVR including display, gamepad,
       audio and speech APIs.
     * [https://www.chromestatus.com/features]Chrome Platform Status
     * [https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/platform/stat
       us/]Edge Platform Status
     * [https://platform-status.mozilla.org/]Firefox Platform Status
     * [https://webkit.org/status/]Webkit Platform Status (Safari)
     * [https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/MDN/Contribute/Structures
       /Compatibility_tables]MDN Compatibility tables - MDN's web
       technology documentation has a browser compatibility table end the
       end of each article.
     * [https://github.com/mdn/browser-compat-data]MDN Browser Compat Data
       - npm module powering the MDN Compatibility tables.
     * [https://github.com/scottjehl/Device-Bugs]Device Bugs & Quirks -
       Crowd sourced collection of weird HTML, CSS, and JS quirks in
       mobile devices, which you won't find in the other support tables.

Testing Methods

   With progressive enhancement you support different experiences in
   different environments. These are some ways to test all these
   variations:
     * [https://opendevicelab.com/]Open Device Lab - Lets you test
       manually on actual devices (for free).
     * [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text-based_web_browser]Text browsers
       - Good way to test if your content is accessible at the baseline.
       Try [http://lynx.browser.org/]Lynx for example.
     * [https://dev.opera.com/articles/making-sites-work-opera-mini/#testi
       ng-in-opera-mini]Testing in Opera Mini - Download the app, emulate
       on desktop, setup to test local websites. (Opera Mini accounts for
       over 5% browser usage world wide)
     * [https://curl.haxx.se/docs/manual.html]cURL - Web page to see the
       pre-rendered source code of a page.
     * [https://www.browserling.com/]Browserling - Lets you manually test
       web pages in different versions of browsers on Windows and Android
       platforms.
     * [https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/tools/vms/mac
       /]Run Internet Explorer using Virtual Machines - To test IE
       browsers on other platforms.
     * [https://developers.google.com/web/tools/chrome-devtools/iterate/de
       vice-mode/testing-other-browsers?hl=en#device-emulators-and-simulat
       ors]Device emulators and simulators
     * [https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/wiki/DesiredCapabilities]Co
       nfigure Desired Capabilities in Selenium - Run automated browser
       tests in different scenarios.
     * Continuously run automated tests in different browsers using
       [https://www.browserstack.com/]BrowserStack,
       [https://saucelabs.com/]Saucelabs or other alternatives.
     * [https://github.com/GoogleChrome/lighthouse]Lighthouse - Audit and
       meassure performance of Progressive Web Apps (via cli or
       [https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/lighthouse/blipmdconlkpi
       nefehnmjammfjpmpbjk]Chrome extension).
     * [http://adaptivewebdesign.info/1st-edition/read/chapter-6.html#the-
       progressive-enhancement-checklist]Progressive Enhancement checklist
       (1st edition, HTML),
       [http://adaptivewebdesign.info/2nd-edition/checklist.pdf]Checklist
       of 2nd edition (PDF) - Actionable list to check you've applied
       Progressive Enhancement best practices. Part of
       [http://adaptivewebdesign.info/]Adaptive Web Design book.

Examples

Custom Form Elements

     * [https://www.sitepoint.com/replacing-radio-buttons-without-replacin
       g-radio-buttons/]Fancy radio buttons - Based on HTML radio buttons,
       visually enhanced using CSS pseudo classes and elements.
     * [https://www.filamentgroup.com/dwpe/checkbox-radiobutton/]Checkboxe
       s & radio buttons - With custom focus, hover and checked state.
       Enhanced asynchronously.
     * [https://ghinda.net/css-toggle-switch/]Toggle switch - Checkbox or
       radios, visually enhanced to sliding toggle switches using CSS
       only.
     * [http://lea.verou.me/2011/08/accessible-star-rating-widget-with-pur
       e-css/]5-star rating - Based on HTML radio buttons, visually
       enhanced using CSS pseudo classes and elements.
     * [https://github.com/filamentgroup/jQuery-Slider]jQuery slider -
       Accessible, custom slider widget based on a standard HTML select.
     * [https://www.filamentgroup.com/lab/jquery-custom-file-input-book-de
       signing-with-progressive-enhancement.html]jQuery custom file input
       - Article and library.
     * [https://github.com/ghengeveld/react-isomorphic-form/]React
       isomorphic form - Set of React form components which can be
       pre-rendered & handled server-side. They are enhanced client-side
       without losing state.

Data Visualisations

     * [https://css-tricks.com/progressive-enhancement-data-visualizations
       /]Timeline - From definition list to SVG illustration (article with
       demos).
     * [https://www.filamentgroup.com/lab/update-to-jquery-visualize-acces
       sible-charts-with-html5-from-designing-with.html]Charts - From data
       table to themed charts using HTML5 canvas (article and library).

Images

     * [http://filamentgroup.github.io/responsive-carousel/test/functional
       /fade-auto.html]Responsive Carousel - List of images enhanced into
       responsive carousel with various behaviour options.
     * [https://github.com/tvler/lazy-progressive-enhancement]Lazy
       Progressive Enhancement - Lazy load images inside <noscript> tags.
       (note: Evergreen browsers only)

Menus

     * [http://heydonworks.com/practical_aria_examples/#hamburger]Progress
       ive hamburger menu - List of links in footer enhanced to off-canvas
       menu.

Page Navigation

   Asynchronously fetch and transition between static pages using ajax and
   history.pushState:
     * [http://barbajs.org/]Barba.js - Add page transitions with event
       hooks, cache and prefetch support.
     * [https://github.com/miguel-perez/smoothState.js]SmoothState.js -
       Add page transitions with event hooks, cache and prefetch support.
       (requires jQuery).
     * [https://github.com/defunkt/jquery-pjax]jquery-pjax - Add page
       transitions with support for multiple containers / content slots
       (requires jQuery).
     * [https://github.com/MoOx/pjax]MoOx/pjax - Similar tot jquery-pjax,
       but without the jQuery dependency.
     * [https://github.com/turbolinks/turbolinks]Turbolinks - Add page
       transitions with event hooks and cache support. Has adapters to
       bind to native navigation controls on iOS and Android.

Related Articles

     * [https://hacks.mozilla.org/2016/07/make-the-web-work-for-everyone/]
       Make the web work for everyone - Plea to developers to consider
       browser differences and build a resilient web.
     * [https://gds.blog.gov.uk/2013/10/21/how-many-people-are-missing-out
       -on-javascript-enhancement/]How many people are missing out on
       JavaScript enhancement? - Research on why in 1.1% of page visits
       JavaScript isn't loaded.
